00:40:44,442 --> 00:40:47,536
So, you are Betty.

473
00:40:50,681 --> 00:40:53,445
I'm surprised.

474
00:40:53,517 --> 00:40:55,451
So am I.

475
00:40:55,519 --> 00:40:57,987
You're not at all alike.

476
00:40:59,723 --> 00:41:04,092
My brother is obviously attracting
more perceptive women these days.

477
00:41:04,161 --> 00:41:07,494
Thank you.
What do you mean, "these days"?

478
00:41:07,565 --> 00:41:10,125
Well, let's just say...

479
00:41:10,201 --> 00:41:12,795
the girls he used to
bring around...

480
00:41:12,870 --> 00:41:15,395
didn't have your class...

481
00:41:15,473 --> 00:41:17,941
or subtlety.

482
00:41:18,008 --> 00:41:21,466
My brother has
a certain charm.

483
00:41:21,545 --> 00:41:25,072
But don't you find him
a little... boring...

484
00:41:25,149 --> 00:41:28,277
a bit, um, limited?

485
00:41:28,352 --> 00:41:30,650
Not yet.

486
00:41:30,721 --> 00:41:32,655
Art says you're an artist.

487
00:41:32,723 --> 00:41:37,888
You can't really say that about a person
until he's been dead at least, uh, ten years.

488
00:41:37,962 --> 00:41:40,487
What a point of view.

489
00:41:40,564 --> 00:41:42,498
That's so pedantic.

490
00:41:42,566 --> 00:41:44,431
- Eh?
- I mean romantic.

491
00:41:44,502 --> 00:41:46,663
Ah.

492
00:41:46,737 --> 00:41:49,069
My sister
would love you.

493
00:41:49,139 --> 00:41:52,074
Why don't you come by with
Art for dinner tonight?

494
00:41:52,142 --> 00:41:54,838
And you can talk about art
and the meaning of life.

495
00:41:54,912 --> 00:41:57,506
- l-l-l...
- I won't take no for an answer.

496
00:41:57,581 --> 00:42:00,948
- 9:00.
- Okay. Okay.

497
00:42:01,018 --> 00:42:03,452
I can't wait
for my brother.

498
00:42:06,624 --> 00:42:09,821
Miss Fletcher,
if my brother shows up...

499
00:42:09,894 --> 00:42:13,386
please tell him
I need to speak to him.

500
00:42:13,464 --> 00:42:15,898
Betty, a pleasure.

501
00:42:15,966 --> 00:42:17,900
Until tonight, then.

502
00:42:17,968 --> 00:42:20,300
Yeah. Tonight.

503
00:42:50,067 --> 00:42:52,695
- Hey! Hi.
- Hi.

504
00:43:10,187 --> 00:43:13,156
<i>- Betty! You been here long?
- No.</i>

505
00:43:13,223 --> 00:43:15,885
- I met your brother.
- Ohh.

506
00:43:15,960 --> 00:43:18,554
- You're right. He's very complicated.
- Yeah.

507
00:43:18,629 --> 00:43:20,620
But you know what?
He would make a great best man.

508
00:43:20,698 --> 00:43:25,533
Fabulous idea!
He'll love that.

509
00:43:25,603 --> 00:43:27,798
I-I am not sure.

510
00:43:27,871 --> 00:43:29,805
- I'll check it out.
- Okay.

511
00:43:29,873 --> 00:43:34,003
<i>Your brother wants you to call
him anyway. It sounded important.</i>

512
00:43:34,078 --> 00:43:38,674
Darling, would you wait for
me in the car? I won't be long.

513
00:43:38,749 --> 00:43:41,343
Okay. You'll be
at the wedding?

514
00:43:41,418 --> 00:43:44,683
- Wouldn't miss it.
- Okay.

515
00:43:55,699 --> 00:43:59,726
<i>You know, I don't mind lying about
the check being in the mail...</i>

516
00:43:59,803 --> 00:44:02,931
or that some kid's
the new Jackson Pollock...

517
00:44:03,007 --> 00:44:07,535
but I just don't think $7.50
an hour covers whatever this is.

518
00:44:07,611 --> 00:44:11,172
Well, you choose.

519
00:44:11,248 --> 00:44:14,012
It's that or back
to the suicide hot line.

520
00:44:17,554 --> 00:44:20,182
- Art?
- What now?

521
00:44:20,257 --> 00:44:24,023
My name is Gloria. Don't you
ever call me Miss Fletcher again.

522
00:44:28,165 --> 00:44:31,100
What are you doing here? Why do
you follow me everyplace that I go?

523
00:44:31,168 --> 00:44:33,398
I'm not following you. I'm looking out
for you. Someone's gotta protect you.

524
00:44:33,470 --> 00:44:35,904
<i>- You can't take care of yourself.
- I don't want your protection.</i>

525
00:44:35,973 --> 00:44:38,908
<i>- I want you to leave me alone.
- What are you doing with this guy?</i>

526
00:44:38,976 --> 00:44:41,570
Yeah, Art, Art, it's...
it's great to see you again.

527
00:44:41,645 --> 00:44:44,739
You know, Betty's been saying
such wonderful things about you.

528
00:44:44,815 --> 00:44:47,010
Don't touch him!
Don't even get near him.

529
00:44:47,084 --> 00:44:50,349
I'm just trying to congratulate him. Anyone
who makes you happy makes me happy.

530
00:44:50,421 --> 00:44:53,015
You are not fooling me, Gene.
I know you.

531
00:44:53,090 --> 00:44:55,957
No, you know the old Gene. I'm not
the same guy. I mean, give me a chance.

532
00:44:56,026 --> 00:44:58,961
l... here. Here.
I brought you some flowers.

533
00:44:59,029 --> 00:45:00,963
- Thank you.
- Beautiful. Beautiful.

534
00:45:01,031 --> 00:45:02,965
- I'm just a warmhearted guy.
- Wh... What are you...

535
00:45:03,033 --> 00:45:04,967
- Hey! Hey!
- What... What are you doing?

536
00:45:05,035 --> 00:45:07,970
What are you doing?
Giving him the kiss of death?

537
00:45:18,182 --> 00:45:21,208
Kiss of death? What kiss of death?
What is that?

538
00:45:21,285 --> 00:45:23,719
He kisses you,
you're history.

539
00:45:23,787 --> 00:45:27,223
<i>- Didn't you ever see The Godfather?
- Which one?</i>

540
00:45:35,199 --> 00:45:37,565
- Just a moment, sir.
- Sure.

541
00:45:47,544 --> 00:45:49,808
<i>You must be Bart.</i>

542
00:45:50,547 --> 00:45:52,481
And you must be Liz.

543
00:45:55,252 --> 00:45:57,914
So Art told you about me?

544
00:45:57,988 --> 00:46:02,015
Well, eh, he tells me
that you two...

545
00:46:02,092 --> 00:46:04,287
got off
on the wrong foot.

546
00:46:04,361 --> 00:46:07,853
That's a very artful way of putting it.

547
00:46:07,931 --> 00:46:10,161
Yeah, I suppose it is.

548
00:46:10,234 --> 00:46:13,795
- I know he comes off as a little, uh...
- Slick?

549
00:46:13,871 --> 00:46:15,896
Uh, slick.
Really?

550
00:46:15,973 --> 00:46:18,373
- I think he's cool.
- Cool, slick. Whatever.

551
00:46:18,442 --> 00:46:21,843
It's... it fits him.
He's a very smooth operator.

552
00:46:21,912 --> 00:46:25,075
He had to be to survive.

553
00:46:25,149 --> 00:46:29,210
- Survive what?
- Well, we grew up without any money.

554
00:46:29,286 --> 00:46:34,155
You know, I was an artist,
and the kids used to kick my ass all the time.

555
00:46:34,224 --> 00:46:37,022
<i>- He protected me.
- Hello, Bart.</i>

556
00:46:37,094 --> 00:46:40,552
- Hi.
- Hi. Art just called and he can't come.

557
00:46:40,631 --> 00:46:43,998
He said there's some kind of problem
with your dad?

558
00:46:44,067 --> 00:46:48,026
Yeah, the old man's got Korsakov's Syndrome.
You know, memory problems.

559
00:46:48,105 --> 00:46:51,006
Well, it was very nice of Art
to let you come.

560
00:46:51,074 --> 00:46:54,737
Very nice. He's got
a very nice side to him.

561
00:46:56,246 --> 00:46:58,214
Dinner's out
on the veranda.

562
00:46:58,282 --> 00:47:01,149
- This way.
- Oh.

563
00:47:01,218 --> 00:47:04,085
- This is a very nice house, hmm?
- Thank you.

564
00:47:04,154 --> 00:47:07,885
- Wow.
- Glad you came?

565
00:47:07,958 --> 00:47:11,189
For me,
there is only Rimbaud.

566
00:47:11,261 --> 00:47:14,025
Rimbaud. Why?

567
00:47:14,097 --> 00:47:17,362
Well, it's obvious.
He's the original.

568
00:47:17,434 --> 00:47:21,268
I mean, Seagal and Van Damme
are just cheap imitations.

569
00:47:23,073 --> 00:47:26,201
I admire him because
he had the good sense...

570
00:47:26,276 --> 00:47:28,471
to quit while he
was still ahead.

571
00:47:28,545 --> 00:47:31,844
I disagree.
I think that two sequels was plenty.

572
00:47:33,217 --> 00:47:37,153
Honey, Rimbaud, not Rambo.
Poet, French, dead.

573
00:47:37,221 --> 00:47:41,453
I'm just trying to change the
subject before I fall asleep...

574
00:47:41,525 --> 00:47:43,459
<i>face down in my plate.</i>

575
00:47:43,527 --> 00:47:46,894
So are you saying that all artists
should quit when they're 18?

576
00:47:46,964 --> 00:47:51,196
Well, no, but th-they should
have enough sense to stop...

577
00:47:51,268 --> 00:47:53,202
when their best work
is behind them.

578
00:47:53,270 --> 00:47:55,932
You're not gonna
smoke that, are you?

579
00:47:56,006 --> 00:47:57,940
No, I'm gonna eat it.

580
00:48:20,697 --> 00:48:23,291
Excuse me.

581
00:48:23,367 --> 00:48:26,461
My ex-brother-in-law.
He's big on drama.

582
00:48:28,538 --> 00:48:30,563
Unlike your sister.

583
00:48:30,641 --> 00:48:33,769
Get off of my dock,
you maniac.

584
00:48:33,844 --> 00:48:38,645
<i>Are you crazy? Somebody should
take you away and, and lock you up.</i>

585
00:48:38,715 --> 00:48:40,979
Do you know what day
this is, darling?

586
00:48:41,051 --> 00:48:46,250
- Yeah, it's the day they take out the trash.
- It's our anniversary.

587
00:48:46,323 --> 00:48:50,020
No, it's not.
Our anniversary is June 8.

588
00:48:50,093 --> 00:48:52,960
Our second anniversary.

589
00:48:53,030 --> 00:48:54,964
You came all the way here
to tell me that?

590
00:48:55,032 --> 00:48:58,365
I've been paying Dr. Huffeyer a lot
of money so that I could forget it.

591
00:49:07,411 --> 00:49:11,677
<i>Remember the church in Cabo?</i>

592
00:49:11,748 --> 00:49:14,945
<i>That funny little priest.</i>

593
00:49:15,018 --> 00:49:17,987
The burro that ate my bouquet.

594
00:49:20,724 --> 00:49:23,056
It's not gonna work.

595
00:49:25,128 --> 00:49:27,961
No, but the music
is great.

596
00:49:30,667 --> 00:49:32,601
Why, thank you.

597
00:49:35,072 --> 00:49:37,006
Hi, there.

598
00:49:38,942 --> 00:49:41,274
Go for it.

599
00:49:51,922 --> 00:49:56,052
Fireworks and flowers are not gonna
do it, Gene, and neither are mariachi.

600
00:49:56,126 --> 00:49:59,653
They were playing this song.

601
00:50:01,465 --> 00:50:04,332
These are the guys.
I flew 'em in first class.

602
00:50:04,401 --> 00:50:08,269
I even had to get Pablo out of prison,
so it would be perfect for you.

603
00:50:13,810 --> 00:50:15,641
Dance with me?

604
00:50:15,712 --> 00:50:18,772
Go away.

605
00:50:20,150 --> 00:50:22,084
Please?

606
00:50:23,754 --> 00:50:25,688
One last time.

607
00:50:25,756 --> 00:50:29,954
On my honor, I-I'll
never bother you again.

608
00:50:32,229 --> 00:50:34,163
Dance with me?

609
00:50:50,247 --> 00:50:53,375
Have you ever been married?

610
00:50:53,450 --> 00:50:55,384
- No.
- Never.

611
00:50:58,722 --> 00:51:00,656
- Hopper.
- Oh.

612
00:51:00,724 --> 00:51:04,387
So Hopper is, uh,
illegitimate.

613
00:51:04,461 --> 00:51:06,895
Yeah.

614
00:51:37,227 --> 00:51:40,822
Would that little monkey
of yours do this for you?

615
00:51:40,897 --> 00:51:45,857
Ooh! If there's an ape
in my life, it's you.

616
00:51:47,637 --> 00:51:51,038
- Get out of here!
- What did I do?

617
00:51:54,544 --> 00:51:58,571
<i>Of all the manipulative,
scum-sucking... Good night.</i>

618
00:51:58,648 --> 00:52:01,617
- Good night.
- I hate you, Eugene Palletto.

619
00:52:01,685 --> 00:52:03,619
So, eh...

620
00:52:05,689 --> 00:52:09,022
do we have to
stop dancing?

621
00:52:09,092 --> 00:52:11,026
- No.
- Nah.

622
00:52:19,536 --> 00:52:23,529
It's as if he wants me to be, like, this
perfect housewife, but we're not even married.

623
00:52:23,607 --> 00:52:25,541
It's so ridiculous.

624
00:52:25,609 --> 00:52:29,340
Then afterwards, you know, it's
really hard for me to be mad at him...

625
00:52:29,412 --> 00:52:32,347
- for too long because I love him so...
- But that's the point.

626
00:52:32,415 --> 00:52:35,942
The machine
creates the tension.

627
00:52:36,019 --> 00:52:38,681
- Bart?
- Hi.

628
00:52:38,755 --> 00:52:41,019
- Hi.
- What a surprise. What are you doing here?

629
00:52:41,091 --> 00:52:43,685
- I work here.
- Uh, that's right, that's right.

630
00:52:43,760 --> 00:52:46,456
- You have time for a coffee?
- Yeah.

631
00:52:46,530 --> 00:52:48,464
- Good. Let's go.
- Okay.

632
00:52:48,532 --> 00:52:51,467
Okay, guys, it was very nice
talking to you, huh?

633
00:52:51,535 --> 00:52:53,469
<i>- Bye-bye.
- All right. Bye.</i>

634
00:52:53,537 --> 00:52:55,471
- Uh-huh.
- All right.

635
00:52:55,539 --> 00:52:58,736
Unfortunately, they don't emphasize
technique these days.

636
00:52:58,808 --> 00:53:02,107
Perfect. You can smother an idea
with technique.

637
00:53:02,179 --> 00:53:05,979
But these kids have things in their heads
they can't get down on paper.

638
00:53:06,049 --> 00:53:08,540
What good is an idea
if it stays up here?

639
00:53:08,618 --> 00:53:11,178
You might as well be
an artist who doesn't paint.

640
00:53:11,254 --> 00:53:14,018
Now, that's my definition
of a coward.

641
00:53:19,629 --> 00:53:22,496
Are you working now?

642
00:53:22,566 --> 00:53:24,500
I can't seem to stop.

643
00:53:24,568 --> 00:53:26,729
I'd love to see
some of your work.

644
00:53:26,803 --> 00:53:30,136
But you just got here,
so there's probably nothing to show yet.

645
00:53:30,207 --> 00:53:33,938
Actually, I shipped
a few pieces here and...

646
00:53:34,010 --> 00:53:36,171
Really?

647
00:53:36,246 --> 00:53:39,238
- If you got a little time...
- Now is good.

648
00:53:39,316 --> 00:53:41,648
- Now?
- Yeah.

649
00:53:41,718 --> 00:53:44,585
Um, okay, great, great.
Uh...

650
00:53:44,654 --> 00:53:49,523
Just, uh, let me make a call,
and we're on our way.

651
00:53:49,593 --> 00:53:51,527
Okay.

652
00:53:55,565 --> 00:53:58,159
Manny, it's Art.
Listen.

653
00:53:58,235 --> 00:54:02,035
You've got to come over to the gallery.
People are going nuts about you.

654
00:54:02,105 --> 00:54:04,972
<i>Art's Gallery.</i>

655
00:54:05,041 --> 00:54:09,102
Gloria, it's me. This is crucial.
You gotta do me a favor.

656
00:54:09,179 --> 00:54:12,512
- Oh, joy.
- Look, Manny'll be there any minute.

657
00:54:12,582 --> 00:54:15,517
- Is he gonna be a twin too?
- This is not a game.

658
00:54:15,585 --> 00:54:19,544
- Keep him there for an hour.
- How do you propose I do that?

659
00:54:19,623 --> 00:54:24,060
<i>Use your charm.</i>

660
00:54:45,915 --> 00:54:48,383
<i>- I'm nervous. Uh...
- Don't be.</i>

661
00:54:49,686 --> 00:54:52,621
<i>You're the first person
to see them in a long time.</i>

662
00:54:58,228 --> 00:55:00,822
They are no big deal,
really.

663
00:55:00,897 --> 00:55:03,695
<i>Bart, they're very good.
I like them.</i>

664
00:55:03,767 --> 00:55:06,668
I like them a lot.

665
00:55:07,737 --> 00:55:09,637
Good.

666
00:55:14,911 --> 00:55:18,677
- Is that yours?
- Yeah.

667
00:55:18,748 --> 00:55:21,546
- I love that.
- Yeah?

668
00:55:23,019 --> 00:55:25,317
It's beautiful.
You know why?

669
00:55:25,388 --> 00:55:27,288
No.

670
00:55:27,357 --> 00:55:30,349
It's both simple
and heartfelt.

671
00:55:40,770 --> 00:55:42,761
Keep it.

672
00:55:42,839 --> 00:55:46,605
- What? Are you kidding?
- Take it. My gift.

673
00:55:46,676 --> 00:55:50,043
- Oh, no, I couldn't.
- Of course you can.

674
00:55:50,113 --> 00:55:52,138
I want you to have it.

675
00:55:52,215 --> 00:55:57,416
Please.

676
00:56:03,827 --> 00:56:06,887
Oh, I love this.

677
00:56:06,963 --> 00:56:09,557
Good.

678
00:56:19,809 --> 00:56:21,743
Well, I better go.

679
00:57:29,379 --> 00:57:32,177
You were very talented.

680
00:57:32,248 --> 00:57:36,207
<i>Todavia no se porque lo
dejaste. Este es muy bueno.</i>

681
00:58:00,410 --> 00:58:02,776
- Hi.
- How was your swim?

682
00:58:19,829 --> 00:58:22,389
Art's Gallery.

683
00:58:22,465 --> 00:58:25,366
Gloria, any messages
for me?

684
00:58:25,435 --> 00:58:28,666
Hillerman. He read about your, "merger
with the Kerner fortune..."

685
00:58:28,738 --> 00:58:30,933
is, I believe,
how he put it...

686
00:58:31,007 --> 00:58:33,874
- so he's raising the rent.
- Any other calls?

687
00:58:33,943 --> 00:58:35,968
One, but it's not
for you.

688
00:58:36,045 --> 00:58:38,980
If you see your brother Bart,
tell him I have a message for him.

689
00:58:39,048 --> 00:58:41,175
Wait, wait, wait!

690
00:58:47,156 --> 00:58:50,421
<i>Art's Gallery.</i>

691
00:58:50,493 --> 00:58:54,486
Gloria, this is Bart.
Do I have any calls?

692
00:58:54,564 --> 00:58:58,159
As it happens, a certain
Liz Kerner called.

693
00:58:58,234 --> 00:59:00,327
She said
she'd call back.

694
00:59:00,403 --> 00:59:03,133
Bart, I'm worried
about your brother.

695
00:59:03,206 --> 00:59:05,902
You should be, Gloria.
We'll discuss it later.

696
00:59:07,977 --> 00:59:10,502
I'm going to fix myself
a drink.

697
00:59:10,580 --> 00:59:13,674
<i>- Anybody want anything?
- I'd love a vodka tonic.</i>

698
00:59:13,750 --> 00:59:16,218
<i>- Liz, what about you?
- No, thanks.</i>

699
00:59:18,488 --> 00:59:21,855
No, Hopper, it's not me. It's not me.

700
00:59:42,979 --> 00:59:45,413
<i>No, cancel that order! Excuse me.</i>

701
00:59:45,481 --> 00:59:48,245
Maria, could you use another phone?
Thank you.

702
00:59:48,318 --> 00:59:51,082
What? What?
No, forget it!

703
00:59:51,154 --> 00:59:53,679
<i>Don't accept those conditions.</i>

704
00:59:53,756 --> 00:59:56,782
Hello?

705
00:59:56,859 --> 01:00:00,454
This is Bart Dodge.
May I speak to Liz, please?

706
01:00:03,833 --> 01:00:06,961
- Hello?
- Liz? It's Bart.

707
01:00:07,036 --> 01:00:09,129
- You called?
- Yeah.

708
01:00:09,205 --> 01:00:11,730
We were having kind of
a lazy day here and...

